<div id="simulation" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">01</span>Simulacra and simulation</h2>
  <p>Baudrillard traces a historical progression in the relationship between representations and reality. First, representations reflect reality — a map corresponds to a territory. Then, they mask and distort reality. Then, they mask the absence of any underlying reality. Finally, they bear no relation to reality at all — they are their own referent, pure simulation.</p>
  <p>He wasn't making a metaphysical claim that reality doesn't exist. He was making a sociological claim: in contemporary media culture, representations have become self-referential. The news refers to other news. Political discourse refers to polling about political discourse. Brands refer to other brands. The chain of signification no longer terminates in something outside itself.</p>
</div>
<div id="hyperreality" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">02</span>Hyperreality</h2>
  <p>The result is hyperreality: a condition in which simulation is more real than the real. Disneyland is more "American" than America. The Gulf War coverage was more vivid than the war. A perfect replica of a medieval village is more medieval than any actual medieval village, which was full of mud and disease.</p>
  <p>This isn't about individual deception. People know Disneyland is fake. The point is that the fake operates more effectively as the referent — produces more affect, more meaning, more orientation — than the reality it supposedly represents. The simulation has eaten the real.</p>
  <div class="callout"><span class="callout-label">For politics</span><p>Political communication in this environment is not about representing positions or persuading about policy. It's about producing the feeling of politics — the sense that something is at stake, that sides exist, that action is occurring. The simulation of political life displaces political life.</p></div>
</div>
<div id="media" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">03</span>The media and political life</h2>
  <p>Baudrillard's media analysis: mass media doesn't transmit information. It produces a particular kind of relationship to the world — passive, spectatorial, consuming. The medium itself, regardless of content, trains people to receive rather than act, to watch rather than participate.</p>
  <p>This connects to Gramsci in an important way: hegemony doesn't require media manipulation. It's built into the form. You don't have to lie to people through television. You just have to get them to watch television. The watching — the passive, spectatorial relationship — is itself the ideological content.</p>
</div>
<div id="commons" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">04</span>Why this matters</h2>
  <p>Baudrillard's analysis is a challenge to any politics built primarily on representation: on making the real conditions of people's lives visible, on raising consciousness through information. If the problem is not a lack of information but a condition in which information itself has lost its grounding, then visibility strategies are insufficient.</p>
  <p>Commons institutions matter in this analysis not primarily as policy alternatives but as different modes of social relation — ones that are irreducibly real because they involve direct cooperation, embodied labor, face-to-face governance. The community land trust, the mutual aid network, the commons — these are not representations of an alternative. They are the alternative, practiced directly. That's different from knowing about an alternative, and the difference matters.</p>
</div>
